                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=69433#69433"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu Sep 16, 2004 10:10 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=69433"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Iumarex wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I personally resent the fact that while one of the items on our top ten list was to reduce the amount of resists to Mez.  They actually cranked up the resist rate.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, but there is nothing at all that you don't resent.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Wow, talk about missing the point of the class. It's one of the class-defining abilities, you know. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Sorry, I disagree with you entirely. It may be class defining for you, but charming is one of many things an enchanter can do, plus its one thing that was completely overkill in the past and a major source of unbalance in EQ. It's got to be fixed.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I want to be a class that gets aggro and doesn't die.
<br />
I want to have options when it happens.
<br />
I enjoy the mental rush of charm, just keep the DPS on mob and on player during break balanced and I'm happy.
<br />
Let my buffs be superceded (BST mana regen -- admittedly, you rolled back paragon2.0, Shaman melee buffs -- haste cap and a total of +15% damage modifier makes SoS's change over SoV look cosmetic), I don't mind.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I agree with everything Yakk said, but this is a good summary of where I stand. The game needs to be fun and challenging in many ways, and fun should not be a direct link to "maximum dps". Ideally there are times charm should not be an option, other times its a limited option, sometimes a good option but perhaps short in duration, other times its a great option but those times are random and hard to find. As a good and well rounded enchanter you should recognise when and how to use your abilities, and one spell line shouldn't ever be the sole option in every circumstance.
<br />

<br />
What if charmed mobs conitinued their lower dps output for a brief time, but an ex-charm pet provides no experience (or almost none) for several minutes after it breaks? It would solve the reverse charm issue that I assume SOE will consider an exploit of the game mechanics. You would have a vested interest in continuing with the same pet, you have a better chance of surviving a pet break, but you still have to be on your toes.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
